# Research Digest #002 130726 Applications of AI in Biotech

**Date:** 130726 
**Paper:**  Applications of Artificial Intelligence in Biotech Drug Discovery and Product Development
**Journal:**  MedComm (2020)2025 Jul 30;6(8):e70317
**Link/DOI:**  doi: 10.1002/mco2.70317

---

## TL;DR
With the craze of Artificial Intelligence in all corners of the world, the paper discusses the prevalence of AI in specifically Drug discovery.

---

## Key Takeaways
- In certain de novo screening, a 75% hit validation was seen
- Nanoparticles were optimized to achieve over 85% functional efficiency
- Workflow of druggable proteome and precision medicine was smoothened by integration of AI-guided optimization
- Generative models include generative adversarial networks, variational autoencoders and diffusion models
- ML and DL models were accelerated for genome sequencing, protein structure predictionm and biomarker identification while maintatining high accuracy and reproducibility
- Discovery and optimization of novel binders ;ie peptides, small proteins, aptamers that reduces the need for excessive experimental screening
- 8 AI-derived drugs has advanced to human studies from 2017-2020 when compared to the traditional ratio of 1:5000 for normal drugs
- Some limitations arose requiring synthetically impractical multistep syntheses despite optimization algorithms
- Training models requires >1000 GPUS thus creates a barrier to entry for less budgeted scientists.
- Complexity of biological systems ensures human scientific expertise are still needed.

---

## My Thoughts
Implementation of AI in Drug and product discovery still requires the mind of a scientist to comprehend and to decide what data is viable. The spike in popularity in AI definitely has attracted many faces to the topic, but the barrier to entry seems so high that only those who put their sweat and and tears into Biology and Artificial Intelligence would reap its benefits.

